---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { articleSchema, faqSchema } from '../../../data/schema.js';
import { topics } from '../../../data/ages.js';

const title = '1–3 Month Old Development: What to Expect';
const description = 'What to expect from your 1 to 3 month old: first social smiles, following objects with their eyes, and growing physical strength — with AAP-backed guidance.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'When will my baby start smiling for real?',
    answer: 'Most babies develop their first "social smile" between 6 and 8 weeks of age. Unlike the involuntary "gas smiles" seen in newborns, a social smile is a response to your face or voice and involves the whole face, especially the eyes.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How much sleep does a 2-month-old need?',
    answer: 'At 2 months, babies typically sleep 14–16 hours in a 24-hour period. While they still wake to feed, you may notice one longer stretch of 4–6 hours at night as their circadian rhythm begins to develop.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Is it normal for my baby to cry more at this age?',
    answer: 'Yes. Crying often peaks around 6–8 weeks of age. This is sometimes called the "period of purple crying." It usually improves significantly by 3–4 months. Always contact your pediatrician if the crying seems excessive or if your baby has a fever.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How much tummy time should my baby do?',
    answer: 'The AAP recommends starting tummy time early. By 2–3 months, aim for 15–30 minutes total per day, broken into short sessions. This helps build the neck and shoulder muscles needed for rolling and sitting.',
  },
];

const aSchema = articleSchema({
  title,
  description,
  url: 'https://ageexpectations.com/ages/1-3-months/',
});
const fSchema = faqSchema(faqs);
---
<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  articleSchema={aSchema}
  faqSchema={fSchema}
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: 'Infant (1–3 Months)' },
  ]}
>
  <h1>1–3 Month Old Development: What to Expect</h1>

  <p>The transition from the newborn phase to early infancy is marked by a wonderful shift: your baby is becoming more aware of the world and more interactive with you. Between 1 and 3 months, you'll likely see the first social smiles, hear the first coos, and notice your baby's physical movements becoming more intentional.</p>

  <p>This period is often when parents feel they are finally getting a "feedback loop" from their baby. This overview covers the key developmental areas for 1–3 month olds, based on guidelines from the American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) and the CDC.</p>

  <h2>Explore 1–3 Month Topics</h2>
  <div class="topic-grid">
    {topics.map(topic => (
      <a href={`/ages/1-3-months/${topic.slug}/`} class="topic-card">{topic.label}</a>
    ))}
  </div>

  <h2>Physical Milestones: Building Strength</h2>

  <p>During these two months, your baby is working hard on motor control. Key physical developments include:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Head Control:</strong> By 2 months, most babies can hold their head up and begin to push up when lying on their tummy. By 3 months, they should have much steadier head control.</li>
    <li><strong>Reaching and Grasping:</strong> The involuntary grasp reflex of the newborn phase begins to fade. Your baby may start to bring their hands to their mouth and may even try to bat at dangling toys.</li>
    <li><strong>Leg Movement:</strong> You'll notice more "bicycle" kicking and smoother leg movements as they build strength for later milestones.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Social and Emotional: The First Smiles</h2>

  <p>This is the age of the social smile — a milestone many parents cherish. Other social developments include:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Social Smiling:</strong> Usually appearing between 6 and 8 weeks, this is a milestone that indicates your baby is beginning to understand social interaction.</li>
    <li><strong>Self-Soothing:</strong> Your baby may begin to suck on their hands or fingers to soothe themselves.</li>
    <li><strong>Attention:</strong> They will start to look at you and follow your movements with their eyes. They are increasingly interested in faces.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Language and Communication: Beyond Crying</h2>

  <p>While crying remains the primary way your baby communicates their needs, new "languages" are emerging:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cooing:</strong> You'll hear "oooh" and "aaah" sounds, especially when you talk to your baby.</li>
    <li><strong>Gurgling:</strong> Vocalizations are becoming more varied as they experiment with their vocal cords.</li>
    <li><strong>Different Cries:</strong> You may start to distinguish between a "hungry" cry, a "tired" cry, and a "change me" cry.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Sensory Development: A Sharper View</h2>

  <p>Your baby's senses are maturing rapidly during this window:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Vision:</strong> By 2–3 months, babies can follow moving objects (tracking) and are beginning to recognize familiar people at a distance. Their color vision is also improving.</li>
    <li><strong>Hearing:</strong> They will turn their head toward sounds and may quiet down or smile in response to the sound of your voice.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Feeding and Sleep</h2>

  <p>At this age, feeding and sleep start to become slightly more predictable, though "routine" is still a loose term:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Feeding:</strong> Most 2-month-olds feed 6–8 times in 24 hours. Growth spurts (often around 6 weeks and 3 months) may cause temporary increases in hunger.</li>
    <li><strong>Sleep:</strong> Total sleep remains high (14–16 hours), but the longest stretch of sleep usually moves to the nighttime. Circadian rhythms are beginning to establish, helped by exposure to daylight during the day and dim lights at night.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="faq-section">
    <h2>Is This Normal? Common Questions About 1–3 Month Development</h2>
    {faqs.map(faq => (
      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-question">{faq.question}</p>
        <p class="faq-answer">{faq.answer}</p>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <div class="callout">
    <h2>When to Talk to Your Pediatrician</h2>
    <p>The AAP recommends well-child visits at 1 month and 2 months. Contact your pediatrician if you notice your 2-to-3-month-old:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Does not respond to loud sounds</li>
      <li>Does not watch things as they move</li>
      <li>Does not smile at people</li>
      <li>Does not bring hands to mouth</li>
      <li>Cannot hold their head up when pushing up on their tummy</li>
      <li>Has a fever of 100.4°F or higher (especially critical for infants under 3 months)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
